Note: ========================================
Note: ARM Assembly Emitter
Note: ========================================
Note: Buffered ARM assembly output. Buffer management is delegated to the
Note: shared byte-buffer foundation in emitter_common.runa. ARM-specific
Note: helpers (emit_integer for decimal numerics, emit_comment with @ prefix,
Note: emit_tab) are retained as thin wrappers over the shared primitives.
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/backends/emitter_common.runa" as EmitterCommon
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as MemoryCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

@Reasoning:
Mirror of the shared 24-byte raw emitter header so callers that want a typed
view of the same memory can use it. The underlying allocation is owned and
managed by the shared emitter_common primitives.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Three packed Integer fields (buffer pointer, capacity, current length) match
the byte layout used by emitter_raw_* helpers at offsets 0, 8, 16. Do not
add fields without updating EMITTER_HEADER_SIZE in emitter_common.runa.
@End Implementation

Type called "ArmEmitter":
    buffer as Integer
    capacity as Integer
    length as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Public constructor for the ARM emitter. Exists so callers do not need to
know that the implementation is the shared raw byte buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_create which allocates a 24-byte header plus an
initial-capacity backing buffer and returns the header pointer (0 on
allocation failure).
@End Implementation

Process called "create_arm_emitter" returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_create from EmitterCommon
End Process

@Reasoning:
Frees the emitter's backing buffer and header. Provided as a named wrapper
so call sites have an ARM-specific name and so the underlying helper can be
swapped without touching every backend.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Delegates to emitter_raw_destroy. Null emitter is safe (returns 1).
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller must not use the emitter after this call; the pointer becomes
dangling. Backend code paths that hold the pointer must drop it.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_arm_emitter" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_destroy from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Public capacity-reservation hook exposed for ARM-specific callers that emit
large operand sequences and want to avoid intermediate reallocations.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_ensure_capacity which geometrically doubles capacity
until the request fits.
@End Implementation

Process called "ensure_capacity" takes emitter as Integer, additional_bytes as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_ensure_capacity from EmitterCommon with emitter, additional_bytes
End Process

@Reasoning:
Thin wrapper around the memory primitive memcpy with argument order kept
backwards (source first, dest second) to match the historical signature in
this module. Used by ARM directive emission code that may need to splice
external buffers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls memory_copy with arguments reordered to (dest, source, size). Caller
owns both buffers; no bounds checking is performed.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller is responsible for ensuring both buffers are valid and at least
`size` bytes long. Misuse causes memory corruption.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "copy_memory" takes source as Integer, dest as Integer, size as Integer:
    proc memory_copy from MemoryCore with dest, source, size
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append a single ASCII byte to the emitter. Hot helper used for punctuation
(spaces, commas, brackets) during ARM assembly generation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_byte which grows the buffer if needed and
appends one byte.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Amortized O(1). On the hot path; do not add overhead here.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_char" takes emitter as Integer, char as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, char
End Process

@Reasoning:
Append a null-terminated string to the emitter. The most-used helper for
mnemonics, register names, and identifiers.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_emit_string which measures the string length once,
then bulk-copies bytes. Empty or null strings are no-ops.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in string length plus an amortized O(1) per growth-doubling.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_string" takes emitter as Integer, string as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, string
End Process

@Reasoning:
Format an integer as a base-10 ASCII decimal and emit it to the buffer.
ARM immediate operands and offsets are written as decimal so the binutils
assembler treats them uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Special-cases negatives (emits '-' then negates) and zero (emits '0'
directly). Otherwise builds the digit sequence into a 32-byte scratch
buffer using modulo-10 / divide-by-10, then emits the digits in reverse
order (most-significant first). Scratch buffer is freed before return.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(log10(value)) digit decomposition plus the same number of emits. The
32-byte scratch buffer is generous for 64-bit integers (max 20 digits).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_integer" takes emitter as Integer, value as Integer:
    Note: Emit an integer as decimal string. Handles negatives and zero.
    If value is less than 0:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 45
        Set value to -value
    End If

    If value is equal to 0:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 48
        Return
    End If

    Let digits be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let digit_count be 0

    While value is greater than 0:
        Let digit be value modulo by 10
        proc memory_set_byte from MemoryCore with digits, digit_count, 48 plus digit
        Set digit_count to digit_count plus 1
        Set value to value divided by 10
    End While

    Let i be digit_count minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let digit_char be proc memory_get_byte from MemoryCore with digits, i
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, digit_char
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    proc deallocate from Layout with digits
End Process

@Reasoning:
Newline emission is broken out so the same byte (LF = 10) can be retuned
later (e.g. CRLF for Windows assemblers) in one place.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single LF (0x0A) byte via emitter_raw_emit_byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_newline" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM-specific indent helper. ARM assembly conventionally uses 4 columns per
nesting level (e.g. inside function bodies, after label/directive headers).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits level * 4 ASCII spaces in a tight loop. Negative or zero level emits
nothing.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(level * 4) - tiny constant factor, fine on the hot path. Could be
replaced with a precomputed indent string for very deep nesting.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "emit_indent" takes emitter as Integer, level as Integer:
    Note: 4-space indentation per ARM assembly readability convention.
    Let total_spaces be level multiplied by 4
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than total_spaces:
        proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM mnemonic-vs-operand separation traditionally uses a hard tab so the
operands align in a single column when viewed in a monospace editor.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits a single HT (0x09) byte.
@End Implementation

Process called "emit_tab" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 9
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM assembly uses "@" (0x40) as the line-comment prefix. Centralising the
prefix here lets ARMv7/ARMv8 dialects share emission code.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Emits "@", then a space, then the null-terminated comment text, then LF.
Comment text is emitted verbatim - the caller must strip any embedded
newlines that would break the single-line comment shape.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Comment text passes through unchanged. Callers should not embed user-
controlled input that could contain newlines without sanitising first.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "emit_comment" takes emitter as Integer, comment_text as Integer:
    Note: Emit ARM assembly comment using "@ " prefix and a trailing newline.
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 64
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 32
    proc emitter_raw_emit_string from EmitterCommon with emitter, comment_text
    proc emitter_raw_emit_byte from EmitterCommon with emitter, 10
End Process

@Reasoning:
Snapshot the emitter's buffer into a freshly allocated null-terminated
copy. Used at end-of-translation to hand a stable string to the caller.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_get_output which allocates `length + 1` bytes,
copies the buffer, and writes a trailing NUL. Returns 0 on allocation
failure. Caller owns the returned pointer.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Caller owns the returned allocation and must free it; the emitter retains
its own buffer for further use or destruction.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_output" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_get_output from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Expose the current write position so callers can mark and patch (e.g.
back-patch branch targets or compute sizes of emitted sequences).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns the 8-byte length field stored in the raw header at offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "get_position" takes emitter as Integer returns Integer:
    Return proc emitter_raw_length from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process

@Reasoning:
Allow reuse of an existing emitter for a fresh translation without
reallocating. Useful when several small translations are emitted in a
loop and the caller wants to reuse the buffer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forwards to emitter_raw_reset which zeros the length field while leaving
the allocated buffer in place.
@End Implementation

Process called "reset" takes emitter as Integer:
    proc emitter_raw_reset from EmitterCommon with emitter
End Process
